Ecological notes : very common in broad-leaved, mixed, pine and carr woodland; conifer plantations; dry and wet heathland; wetlands including fens, mires, bogs, wet meadows, sedge bed and
Sphagnum
kettlehole; parkland; grounds of horticultural research station; gardens; grassland and scrub; marginal vegetation by upland lake; thrift flush; sea cliff; salt marshes and reed beds; rocky island with seabird colonies; very common in open montane habitats. Reared from decaying vegetable matter; orchids and rotten log. ii–xi.
